        body: {
          mechanism: 'Network segmentation divides a network into isolated zones with controlled communication between them. VLANs (Virtual LANs) separate hosts at Layer 2 — hosts in different VLANs cannot communicate directly without passing through a router or firewall. A DMZ (Demilitarized Zone) is a segment that sits between the internet and the internal network, hosting public-facing services (web, email, DNS) in isolation from internal systems. Microsegmentation applies granular per-workload policies — typically in cloud or data center environments — so that even hosts within the same network zone cannot communicate unless explicitly permitted.',
          example: 'A company without segmentation: an attacker compromises a public web server and immediately has network-level access to the internal database, HR systems, and domain controllers on the same flat network. With segmentation: the web server is in a DMZ VLAN. It can reach the application server on port 8080 only. The app server can reach the database on port 5432 only. The database has no path to the domain controllers. A web server compromise does not imply database or AD access.',
          impact: 'Flat networks are the primary enabler of catastrophic lateral movement. Ransomware campaigns and nation-state intrusions consistently exploit the ability to move from an initial foothold (often a workstation or perimeter-facing server) to domain controllers and backup systems. Segmentation does not prevent the initial compromise but limits how far the attacker can go.',
          defense: 'Design network zones around trust level and data sensitivity: internet-facing DMZ, application tier, database tier, management network, and user network — each with explicit, deny-by-default firewall rules between them. Apply microsegmentation in cloud environments using security groups scoped to specific ports and sources. Audit east-west firewall rules regularly — these accumulate exceptions over time and drift toward permissiveness. Include network segmentation in incident response planning — the ability to isolate a segment is a critical containment tool.',
        },
