          example: 'An analyst captures traffic on an internal network and applies the filter http.request.method == "POST". One request to an internal app shows credentials in the POST body — plaintext, no TLS. Following the TCP stream reveals the full login sequence including the session cookie set in the response. Another filter, dns, shows a host making hundreds of DNS queries per second to random subdomains — a sign of DNS tunneling or malware C2 beaconing.',
          impact: 'Packet capture is used in both attack and defense. Attackers use it to harvest credentials from cleartext protocols and session tokens. Defenders use it for incident investigation, protocol debugging, anomaly detection, and verifying that sensitive traffic is actually encrypted in transit. It also exposes metadata in encrypted traffic — timing, packet sizes, destination IPs — that can reveal behavior even without decrypting the payload.',
          defense: 'Eliminate cleartext protocols: replace FTP with SFTP, Telnet with SSH, plain SMTP with STARTTLS or SMTPS, and plain HTTP with HTTPS+HSTS. Use network encryption (VPN or mTLS) for internal service-to-service traffic on sensitive segments. Restrict promiscuous mode access — most OSes require root or a specific capability to enable it. For defense, deploy network monitoring with packet capture on ingress/egress points and critical internal segments.',
