          mechanism: 'Modern systems stack multiple mitigations to make memory corruption harder to exploit. ASLR (Address Space Layout Randomization): randomizes the base addresses of the stack, heap, and libraries on each execution — an attacker cannot hardcode the address of shellcode or a ROP gadget. NX/DEP (No-Execute / Data Execution Prevention): marks the stack and heap as non-executable — shellcode placed in a data region cannot be jumped to and executed. Stack canaries: a random value placed between local variables and the saved return address — checked on function return, so a sequential stack overflow that overwrites the return address also overwrites the canary, triggering termination. PIE (Position-Independent Executable): extends ASLR to the executable itself, randomizing the base address of the main binary.',
