        certs: ['Security+', 'CEH'],
        available: true,
        body: {
          mechanism: 'OAuth 2.0 is an authorization delegation framework — it lets a user grant a third-party application limited access to their account without sharing credentials. Core flow (Authorization Code): user is redirected to the authorization server, authenticates, grants scopes, and is redirected back to the app with a short-lived code. The app exchanges the code server-side for access and refresh tokens. OpenID Connect (OIDC) layers identity on top of OAuth — it adds an ID token (a signed JWT) that conveys who the user is, enabling SSO. Common grant types: Authorization Code (web apps), PKCE extension (SPAs and mobile), Client Credentials (machine-to-machine, no user), and the deprecated Implicit flow.',
          example: 'An OAuth attack via open redirect: the authorization server allows any redirect_uri that starts with the app\'s domain. An attacker crafts a URL with redirect_uri=https://app.com/../../attacker.com. If the server validates only the prefix, the authorization code is delivered to the attacker. They exchange it for tokens and access the victim\'s account. State parameter missing: without a random state value tied to the user\'s session, an attacker can initiate an OAuth flow and trick the victim into completing it — logging the victim into the attacker\'s account (account linking CSRF).',
          impact: 'OAuth misconfiguration is extremely common and often critical — it can lead to account takeover without credentials. Common findings: missing or predictable state parameter (CSRF), overly permissive redirect_uri validation (token theft), insufficient scope validation (privilege escalation), and long-lived tokens without rotation. ID token verification failures in OIDC allow impersonation if the signature or audience claim is not checked.',
          defense: 'Validate redirect_uri against an exact allowlist — no wildcards, no prefix matching. Always use and verify the state parameter to prevent CSRF. Use PKCE for public clients. Validate ID token signatures and all claims (iss, aud, exp) on every request. Issue short-lived access tokens and rotate refresh tokens on use. Request only the scopes actually needed.',
        },
